				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">HSBC to Sidestep European Union Bonus Cap as It Cuts Costs</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Julia Werdigier and Jenny Anderson			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-02-24T16:28:23+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">February 24, 2014 11:28 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">February 24, 2014 11:28 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div class="w225 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/02/25/business/dbpix-hsbc/dbpix-hsbc-blog225.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/02/25/business/dbpix-hsbc/dbpix-hsbc-blog225.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/02/25/business/dbpix-hsbc/dbpix-hsbc-blog225.jpg" id="100000002731680" width="225" height="144" alt="A branch of HSBC in Chinatown in London."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="144"><meta itemprop="width" content="225"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">A branch of HSBC in Chinatown in London.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Facundo Arrizabalaga/European Pressphoto Agency</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/02/24/hsbc-lays-out-new-pay-plan-for-top-executives/" data-title="HSBC to Sidestep European Union Bonus Cap as It Cuts Costs" data-description="The bank said it would pay an allowance to high-ranking executives in order to circumvent European compensation limits and announced earnings for 2013 that fell short of analyst expectations.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="update" id="t21h14m">Updated, 9:14 p.m. | </span>LONDON &#8212; As it reported a profit for last year that fell short of analystsâ estimates, <a title="HSBCâs results release for 2013. (PDF)" href="//www.hsbc.com/investor-relations/investing-in-hsbc/%7E/media/HSBC-com/InvestorRelationsAssets/annual-results-2013/hsbc-holding-ar-2013-media-release.pdf" target="_blank">HSBC</a> on Monday laid out how it was changing its compensation for senior executives, becoming the first major bank here to describe in detail how it was circumventing a new <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/e/european_union/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More articles about the European Union.">European Union</a> cap on bonuses.</p>
<div id="nyt_preview_body">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=HSBC&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about HSBC Holdings PLC.">HSBC</a> also reported on Monday that its profit for last year fell short of analystsâ estimates and that it had missed some of its own cost-cutting targets as revenue fell. The bankâs shares were down almost 3 percent in trading in London on Monday.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The bank, based in London, said that it would award 665 of its senior managers â including its chief executive, Stuart T. Gulliver, and Iain Mackay, its chief financial officer â a fixed-pay allowance as part of their compensation. The allowance, which qualifies neither as a salary nor a bonus, would be exempt from recent European Union rules that limit bonuses to twice a senior employeeâs salary.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Banking giants in London, including <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=BCS&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Barclays PLC">Barclays</a>, <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=GS&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Goldman Sachs Group Inc">Goldman Sachs</a> and <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=BAC&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Bank of America Corporation">Bank of America</a> <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/news/business/companies/merrill_lynch_and_company/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Merrill Lynch &#038; Co.">Merrill Lynch</a>, have been seeking new ways to compensate their senior employees after efforts by the financial services industry to lobby in Brussels against the new bonus rules failed. Britain has filed a lawsuit in the European Court of Justice challenging the bonus cap, which applies to pay as of Jan. 1, 2014.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Banks, not surprisingly, have been critical of the European Union rule. Executives say that banking is a global enterprise and that compensation limits in Europe will drive talent to Asia and the United States. Antony Jenkins, the chief executive of Barclays, came under fire this month when he <a title="DealBook post." href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/02/11/barclays-announces-up-to-12000-job-cuts/" target="_blank">raised investment banking bonuses</a> by 13 percent while reporting huge layoffs and lower profits. âWe need to recruit people from Singapore to San Francisco,â he said. âWe need the best people in the bank to drive long-term sustainable returns for our shareholders.â He predicted that pay for bankers would go down in coming years. Regulators around the world have spent years studying bankersâ sky-high pay levels and trying to determine whether compensation structures like bonuses played a role in the global financial crisis by encouraging reckless behavior. Many officials in the United States and Europe concluded that bonuses should be deferred over long periods of time and that banks should be able to reclaim awards in cases of misconduct.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Policy makers are now lamenting that the new compensation might undermine those goals. âA crude bonus cap does nothing to incentivize higher standards,â Andrew Tyrie, a member of the British Parliament and the chairman of its Treasury Select Committee, <a title="News release by Mr. Tyrie." href="//www.politicshome.com/uk/article/93488/andrew_tyrie_a_crude_bonus_cap_does_nothing_to_incentivise_higher_standards.html" target="_blank">said on Monday</a>. âWhat we need is a fundamental reform of the bonus culture â including much longer deferral and much greater scope for clawback.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Tyrie noted a recent warning by Andrew Bailey, head of the Prudential Regulatory Authority, that the bonus cap, and the allowances and role-based pay that have been put in place to respond to it, would make his job of promoting the safety and soundness of banks more difficult. âIt looks like he is right,â Mr. Tyrie said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Gulliver said that the allowances were not the direction the bank hoped to take. âI think we had a compensation plan that shareholders liked,â he said. âSadly, because of the E.U. directive, weâve had to change.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In reporting on its 2013 results on Monday, HSBC, one of Europeâs largest lenders, said pretax profit rose 9 percent to $22.6 billion, from $20.7 billion in the year earlier. A group of analysts surveyed by Bloomberg had expected earnings to rise to $24.6 billion. Revenue fell 5.4 percent in the year.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe results were at the lower end of expectations, with difficulties in Latin America taking their toll,â said Keith Bowman, an analyst at the stockbroker Hargreaves Lansdown in London. âFurthermore, some management efficiency targets were missed.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Gulliver has closed or sold 63 businesses or investments since 2011 as he plans to focus on corporate finance products and services for faster-growing markets, including Asia and Latin America. As part of the cost-cutting measures, the bank also eliminated about 40,000 jobs.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But lowering costs is taking more time than the bank and analysts expected. Return on equity, a measure of profitability, was 9.2 percent in 2013, short of Mr. Gulliverâs own goal of more than 12 percent.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The bank said it would continue with the strategy it announced in 2011 to cut costs, increase dividends and improve its risk and compliance controls to avoid any potential threat from financial misdeeds. HSBC said it planned further cost savings of $2 billion to $3 billion by improving some of its processes and procedures.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The earnings âreflected the good progress we have made in implementing the strategy that we set out in 2011,â Mr. Gulliver said in a statement.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">HSBC said it paid Mr. Gulliver a bonus of 1.8 million pounds, or $3 million, for last year. That compares with Â£700,000 for 2012, when HSBC agreed to a fine to settle charges with United States authorities that the bank breached rules against money laundering.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">HSBC, which generates most of its earnings from Asia, said the âsharp sell-offâ in some emerging markets was more âa reflection of specific circumstances rather than a generalized threat.â But it predicted developing economies would experience âgreater volatility in 2014 and choppy markets as adjustments are made to changing economic circumstances and sentiment.â</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Julia Werdigier reported from London, and Jenny Anderson from New York.</em></p>
	</div>
